Creating a positive pressure environment using a commercial rooftop unit (RTU) in a ~3,200 ft open space with ~1620 ft ceilings is absolutely possiblebut it requires careful balancing of outside air intake, return air volume, and building envelope pressure.

Lets break it down:

Quick Specs from What You Shared

  • Space size: ~3,200 ft (40' x 40' x 2 sections)
  • Ceiling height average: ~18 ft Volume 57,600 ft
  • Unit size: 7.510 tons (approx. 3,0004,000 CFM of supply airflow)
  • Goal: Positive pressure (like a clean room or hospital) to push air out when doors open, keeping flies and dust out.

Creating Positive Pressure (Key Rule)

To establish positive pressure, you must supply more air into the space than you remove. This usually means:

  • Bringing in more Outside Air (OA) than is returned.
  • Having less exhaust or return air pulled out than is pushed in.

A general rule for modest positive pressurization is to bring in 1015% more supply air than return/exhaust.

Can This Be Done with an RTU Alone?

Yesbut conditionally.

Most standard RTUs have:

  • An economizer damper or dedicated outside air intake (OA).
  • A return plenum or duct for indoor air.
  • A supply fan pushing air into the space.

If the RTU has an economizer or modulating OA damper:

  • You can increase the OA damper setpoint to bring in more outside air than standard.
  • Ideally, you'd aim for 1020% of total supply CFM as OA to begin pressurizing.
  • Some units even allow for adjustable minimum OA via BAS (Building Automation System).

Limitations / Considerations

  1. You cant just add OA indefinitelythe RTU must be able to:

    • Cool/dehumidify that extra air, especially in Florida.
    • Handle the extra static pressure (depends on blower capacity).
    • Maintain CO2 levels and humidity comfort.

  2. If you have ducted return, restricting it slightly (manual damper) while increasing OA can work.

  3. If return is plenum (open above ceiling):

    • Youd need to modulate OA intake higher and possibly add a relief damper to maintain control.

Modifications That Can Help:

  • Barometric relief damper or powered exhaust to avoid over-pressurization.
  • Upgrade economizer or add MUA (Make-Up Air) controls.
  • Add a motorized OA damper with a timed or sensor-based control scheme.
  • CO2 sensors or pressure sensors for fine-tuned pressurization logic.

Extra Ducting? Only If...

If:

  • OA intake is undersized
  • Return is non-adjustable
  • You dont have a way to modulate or override the damper

...then yes, dedicated ducting for OA or separate MUA system may be needed to get clean, balanced airflow.

Quick Thought Experiment:

Say your RTU is supplying 3,500 CFM. You want 15% positive pressure margin:

  • OA required = ~525 CFM minimum
  • Return should ideally be around 2,9003,000 CFM
  • Rest is OA pushing into space, and out through natural gaps/doors.

Thatll create that "hospital" air-rush feeling and keep pests out.

Summary

  • Yes, you can likely do this with RTU modification alone.
  • Adjust OA intake via economizer or damper control.
  • Possibly restrict return airflow slightly or ensure relief venting.
  • Monitor humidity and CO2 if going high on OA %.
